to us in a great way.

00:04:35.410 --> 00:04:39.000
Also today, I invite your
questions at the end,

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.410
but just be aware that
because we're webcasting this

00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:44.760
for future broadcast,

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:47.930
you're kind of implicitly
giving your permission

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:52.300
to be videotaped in the program.

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:56.120
So without further ado,
I'd like to go ahead

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:59.420
and introduce our
speaker for today.

00:04:59.420 --> 00:05:03.680
Betul Basaran received her
PhD in Near Eastern Languages

00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:07.940
and Civilizations from the
University of Chicago in 2006.

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:11.790
And now, she's the associate
professor of Religious Studies

00:05:11.790 --> 00:05:14.820
at St. Mary's College
in Maryland.

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:17.350
She is a historian of
the Islamic Middle East

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:21.390
and her primary area of
expertise, the social economic

00:05:21.390 --> 00:05:26.380
and legal history of the Ottoman
Empire in the early modern era.

00:05:26.380 --> 00:05:29.480
At St. Mary's College, she
teaches various courses

00:05:29.480 --> 00:05:34.430
in the cross-disciplinary
areas of Asian studies, women,

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:39.470
gender and sexuality studies,
history and religious studies.

00:05:39.470 --> 00:05:42.710
She uses an integrated
comprehensive approach

00:05:42.710 --> 00:05:45.840
in her classes with an
emphasis on cultural--

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:49.540
cross-cultural encounters
between the Muslim world,

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:52.010
Europe and the Mediterranean.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:55.690
She is the author of "Selim
III, Social Order and Policing

00:05:55.690 --> 00:05:59.290
in Istanbul at the End
of the Eighteenth Century

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:02.600
between Crisis and Order"
and has published a number

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:04.790
of book chapters on the artisans

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:08.040
and populations of
Ottoman Istanbul.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:11.860
She has also worked extensively
in the Ottoman Archives

00:06:11.860 --> 00:06:15.700
and taught Ottoman language and
paleontology at the University

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:18.670
of Chicago and Georgetown
University.

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:22.420
Her latest project is on
urban space and mobility

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:24.250
with the focus on
the surveillance

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:26.550
of dangerous classes
of the Ottoman

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:29.840
and European cities,
very fascinating.

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:31.220
So without further ado, I'd

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:34.310
like to welcome Betul
Basaran to the podium.

00:06:34.310 --> 00:06:36.110
Thank you.

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:41.350
[ Applause ]

00:06:41.350 --> 00:06:42.650
&gt;&gt; Betul Basaran:
I'm really happy

00:06:42.650 --> 00:06:44.260
and excited to be here today.

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:48.820
The Library of Congress
for historian

00:06:48.820 --> 00:06:51.150
and a bookworm is a
fascinating place.

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:52.450
It's like a dream.

00:06:52.450 --> 00:06:56.210
So, to be here talking to an
interested audience is amazing.

00:06:56.210 --> 00:07:00.460
And I'm also thrilled to see
some old friends and new friends

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:03.850
who are interested in
what I have to say today.

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:09.080
So, I want to say a few
things about myself first in--

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:12.450
before I start talking
about our topic today.

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:15.650
So, I was born and
raised in Turkey

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:17.930
in a very, very secular family.

00:07:17.930 --> 00:07:23.420
And anything associated with
the Ottoman Empire or the Sharia

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:28.830
or Islam, these were not
passwords in my household.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:33.660
My family, I would say had
high expectations for me.

00:07:33.660 --> 00:07:37.470
I was sent to a private
American school.

00:07:37.470 --> 00:07:40.220
I did international
relations for my BA.

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:43.780
So, I was going to become this
great diplomat and bring peace

00:07:43.780 --> 00:07:46.050
to the Middle East, solve the
crisis in the Middle East,

00:07:46.050 --> 00:07:50.220
all of that, probably
working for a Western NGO

00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:54.030
or the European Union or the
NATO or something like that.

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:58.870
So when I told them I was
going to go into a PhD

00:07:58.870 --> 00:08:04.350
in Ottoman history, they were
not thrilled to say the least,

00:08:04.350 --> 00:08:06.920
especially when I became
interested in the sort

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:10.950
of workings of Sharia law
and Muslim Women's agency,

00:08:10.950 --> 00:08:14.810
things of that sort, it didn't
really make much sense to them.

00:08:14.810 --> 00:08:17.040
And the reason I
bring that up today is

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:20.270
because I really feel
very strongly that because

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:25.440
of that modern Turkish
nationalist narrative,

00:08:25.440 --> 00:08:31.330
the official narrative, plus the
orientalist European narrative,

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:36.300
those two things combined have
really had a pretty devastating

00:08:36.300 --> 00:08:40.240
impact on our understanding of
the nuances and complexities

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:43.790
of both Islamic and
Ottoman history.

00:08:43.790 --> 00:08:49.620
So, part of what I do in my
teaching and my research is try

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:52.730
to really question that
and ask the questions

00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:56.620
that I really wasn't encouraged
to ask from a young age.

00:08:56.620 --> 00:08:59.450
So, I remember going
to Istanbul for--

00:08:59.450 --> 00:09:02.560
I grew up in Izmir on the
western coast of Turkey,

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:05.550
going to Istanbul for the
first time to visit some

00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:08.130
of the Ottoman monuments,
this is back

00:09:08.130 --> 00:09:12.110
when they didn't really have
good translations in science

00:09:12.110 --> 00:09:14.940
and either in modern
Turkish or in English.

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:18.130
And I just couldn't read
any of the Ottoman script

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:20.190
on these amazing
buildings and monuments

00:09:20.190 --> 00:09:21.660
and fountains and mosques.

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:22.960
I had no idea.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:24.260
It was so bizarre.

00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:26.890
It was like a schizophrenic
experience

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:30.720
to go see these places where a
hundred years ago people spoke

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:33.820
or wrote in a different
language and read

00:09:33.820 --> 00:09:36.350
that stuff and knew what it was.

00:09:36.350 --> 00:09:38.830
So as a teenager, I was
intrigued but it wasn't

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:40.850
until I went into
graduate school

00:09:40.850 --> 00:09:44.170
that I really started
asking the questions,

00:09:44.170 --> 00:09:50.950
especially about the way the
rhetoric about modernization

00:09:50.950 --> 00:09:53.310
in Turkey and Turkey's
secularization

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:55.750
and modernization, the
way it's been presented

00:09:55.750 --> 00:10:00.510
as a phenomenon that's
been welcomed by all people

00:10:00.510 --> 00:10:02.030
of all classes and backgrounds

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:04.290
as if there were no
nuances or complexities.

00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:08.090
So to ask the question--
questions about, well,

00:10:08.090 --> 00:10:09.830
how did this impact
other people?

00:10:09.830 --> 00:10:11.600
I know my family
really benefited

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:15.160
from these developments
and I had a great education

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:18.300
and I'm grateful for the legal
privileges and the equal rights

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:21.200
that I have under the law,

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:23.770
but how did this impact other
people, what are different ways

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:27.080
of thinking about this
history that happened in my 20s

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.640
which I think is kind of sad,

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:32.950
but better late than
never, I guess.

00:10:32.950 --> 00:10:39.830
So, that's how I came into
the study of things Ottoman.

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:42.850
And so when I first read
the works of Fernand Braudel

00:10:42.850 --> 00:10:47.860
on the Mediterranean,
I was really sad

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:53.040
to see him conceptualize the
Ottoman Empire as the antithesis

00:10:53.040 --> 00:10:55.630
of everything European
and modern

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:59.320
or as really anti-Europe
is what he calls it,

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:05.980
and wanted to do some research
and gear my teaching toward how

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:11.430
to study Mediterranean societies
and the Ottoman Empire as one

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:15.550
and the-- or as partners
in this shared cultural

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:18.360
political environment.

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:21.800
So even though I would
argue, it's fair to say

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:24.950
that the Ottoman state,
Ottoman society was certainly

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:29.870
distinctive, I would argue that
it wasn't exceptional either

00:11:29.870 --> 00:11:35.280
in its militarism, its
brutality, its religious fervor,

00:11:35.280 --> 00:11:37.550
or its misogyny or
patriarchy, right?

00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:42.880
So, there are ways in which
people in this geography

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:45.120
and especially women
since we're talking

00:11:45.120 --> 00:11:50.710
about women shared a culture
of patriarchy regardless

00:11:50.710 --> 00:11:57.020
of religious difference in all
of these Abrahamic traditions.

00:11:57.020 --> 00:11:59.610
So, we have to think about
Ottoman women's experience

00:11:59.610 --> 00:12:01.980
within that broader context
and I'm going to try to do

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:05.320
that as much as possible in
the rather short time period

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:09.710
that we have to the
best of my ability.

00:12:09.710 --> 00:12:17.230
So, let's start with
the Ottoman Empire.

00:12:17.230 --> 00:12:21.350
This is-- All right.

00:12:21.350 --> 00:12:24.080
So, there are some of
you here who know a lot

00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:25.660
about the Ottoman
Empire already.

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:28.730
So if this is repetitive,
I apologize.

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:33.340
So, this is a map that
shows the Ottoman Empire

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:35.370
around the beginning
of the 18th century

00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:39.600
at its sort of fullest borders.

00:12:39.600 --> 00:12:45.430
And as many of you know,
the Ottoman Empire ended

00:12:45.430 --> 00:12:51.350
after World War I and the modern
Turkish Republic replaced it

00:12:51.350 --> 00:12:55.500
or inherited that legacy,
but that legacy is built

00:12:55.500 --> 00:12:58.800
on complete rejection
of everything Islamic

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:03.070
and everything Ottoman
until fairly recently.

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:06.970
So when we talk about Ottoman
subjects, we're talking

00:13:06.970 --> 00:13:08.300
about all of these people

00:13:08.300 --> 00:13:11.640
in this geography even
though my research focuses

00:13:11.640 --> 00:13:14.250
on Istanbul more specifically.

00:13:14.250 --> 00:13:16.880
We have to remember that
this was a multi-religious,

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:19.880
multi ethnic empire.

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:23.140
So, we're not just talking about
Muslim Ottomans, Muslim men

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:26.730
and women, but we're
talking about Christian,

00:13:26.730 --> 00:13:29.840
Jewish and Muslim men and
women and we're talking

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.210
about free people and
enslaved people, right?

00:13:32.210 --> 00:13:34.570
There were also slaves
in-- on this geography.

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:37.860
So, I'm going to try to-- really
my snapshots, this is an attempt

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:42.410
to give you snapshots of
some examples, certainly not

00:13:42.410 --> 00:13:48.500
in any way all inclusive
or comprehensive.

00:13:48.500 --> 00:13:53.840
So, who are the Ottoman women
I'm going to try to talk about.

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:58.890
As I said, I'm not going to
talk only about Muslim women.

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:03.650
This is a picture from the 19th
century and clearly stage one

00:14:03.650 --> 00:14:07.690
from like a postcard, but
that shows a Jewish woman,

00:14:07.690 --> 00:14:10.200
a Bulgarian woman
and a Muslim woman.

00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:15.500
The reason I start with
this picture is to remind us

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:20.990
that the daily lives
and lifestyles of women

00:14:20.990 --> 00:14:24.800
until the modern era didn't
really differ a great deal,

00:14:24.800 --> 00:14:26.100
right, in this geography.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:29.420
We tend to really create
these binaries between Muslims

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:32.400
and everyone else, but
it's certainly historically

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:33.700
is inaccurate.

00:14:33.700 --> 00:14:41.380
Here is an Armenian peasant
woman from South Eastern Turkey.

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:46.220
And I like that she's
smoking a cigarette.

00:14:46.220 --> 00:14:50.130
So, I had to-- I don't
know, she could do that.

00:14:50.130 --> 00:14:56.340
Here is how a Fazil
Enderuni in the 18th century,

00:14:56.340 --> 00:14:59.530
the person who illustrated
this manuscript,

00:14:59.530 --> 00:15:01.970
represented an Istanbul lady

00:15:01.970 --> 00:15:10.260
in the 18th century wearing
this special type of shoes.

00:15:10.260 --> 00:15:14.070
So, that's one way, another way
to think about Ottoman women.

00:15:14.070 --> 00:15:17.200
And here is a-- from
the same work,

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:19.640
a scene of women just
chilling at this--

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:22.240
in this garden at the
park and there are a lot

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.380
of different things
going on in this picture.

00:15:24.380 --> 00:15:28.150
So, I'll leave you with this
for a while as I proceed.

00:15:28.150 --> 00:15:32.920
But as-- like I said, I'm going
to give you some snapshots of--

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:37.760
from the shared world of
Muslim and dhimmi or zimmi

00:15:37.760 --> 00:15:43.080
in Ottoman Turkish that is
non-Muslim protected peoples

00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:45.160
of the book, Jewish
and Christian women

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:47.920
and then both free
and slave women

00:15:47.920 --> 00:15:52.200
and their experiences
in the courts.

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:55.800
And since we're talking about
courts, it's important to start

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:57.950
with a few things
about the legal system

00:15:57.950 --> 00:15:59.830
in the Ottoman Empire.

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:06.500
Obviously, the Ottomans
created an empire that was--

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:09.600
that had Islam as
its primary religion.

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:12.600
But as a multi-ethnic and
multi-religious empire,

00:16:12.600 --> 00:16:18.460
they had multiple legal systems
functioning in the empire

00:16:18.460 --> 00:16:22.340
that were to sort of
different purposes.

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:28.210
So, the part of the legal system
that apply to Muslim subjects

00:16:28.210 --> 00:16:35.380
of the Empire came from-- or
was based on the dual systems

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:39.780
of the Sharia or Islamic--
collection of Islamic principles

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:46.730
and also what's known as the
Kanun, the sultanic secular laws

00:16:46.730 --> 00:16:50.380
and law codes that
were passed based

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:53.050
on the authority of monarchs.

00:16:53.050 --> 00:16:57.780
And these two sets of laws
guided the legal system

00:16:57.780 --> 00:17:01.780
basically, but they were
meant to apply only in theory

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:05.730
to Muslim subjects
of the empire.

00:17:05.730 --> 00:17:08.090
So, Christian and
Jewish subjects

00:17:08.090 --> 00:17:11.920
of the empire were not
subjected to the same laws.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:15.110
The Ottomans recognized these
groups as separate nations,

00:17:15.110 --> 00:17:18.830
millet is the Turkish
word used for it

00:17:18.830 --> 00:17:21.440
and they granted the
religious leaders

00:17:21.440 --> 00:17:24.360
of these groups very detailed

00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:28.160
and specific administrative
fiscal and legal powers.

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:32.260
So, they had authority to
adjudicate and hear cases

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:36.640
in their own courts to regulate
private and spiritual education,

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:43.310
welfare, hospitals,
burials, cemeteries, clergy,

00:17:43.310 --> 00:17:48.030
their own clergy, maintenance
of their houses of worship,

00:17:48.030 --> 00:17:51.780
collection of taxes,
but also family law,

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:54.140
so matters of inheritance,
marriage, divorce,

00:17:54.140 --> 00:18:03.230
custody plus any kind of sales,
sale of property, guardianships,

00:18:03.230 --> 00:18:04.990
dowries, things of that nature.

00:18:04.990 --> 00:18:08.990
So for all of these matters,
Jewish and Christian subjects

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:11.790
of the Ottoman Empire
technically had

00:18:11.790 --> 00:18:13.690
to go to their own courts.

00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:18.590
And as you can imagine, the
clergy also wanted to keep it

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:22.790
that way because it was
within their authority

00:18:22.790 --> 00:18:28.630
to oversee the proper
functioning of those systems.

00:18:28.630 --> 00:18:32.500
So within that broader
picture, let's talk a little bit

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:37.190
about what kind of rights,
legal rights women had.

00:18:37.190 --> 00:18:40.420
I'm going to talk about
the Sharia courts mainly,

00:18:40.420 --> 00:18:42.680
Sharia and Kanun.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.560
But since we're going to
talk-- well, I choose--

00:18:45.560 --> 00:18:48.400
I chose to talk today
mainly about family law,

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:51.840
it's going to be mostly
Sharia principles rather

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:54.040
than secular law codes.

00:18:54.040 --> 00:18:58.410
So, what kinds of
rights did women have?

00:18:58.410 --> 00:19:00.700
I would say that
although gender inequality

00:19:00.700 --> 00:19:04.830
and male dominance clearly
prevailed in Islamic family law

00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:07.770
and its application in
the Ottoman context,

00:19:07.770 --> 00:19:13.020
especially through man's right
to unilateral repudiation

00:19:13.020 --> 00:19:15.180
of marriage known as
talaq which I'll talk

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:18.850
about a little bit
later, polygamy,

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:20.990
concubinage for example.

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:22.370
Despite these things, research

00:19:22.370 --> 00:19:24.960
on Ottoman family law
clearly suggests especially

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:28.320
since the '70s, but more
so in the last two decades

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:29.770
that Christian, Jewish

00:19:29.770 --> 00:19:33.470
and Muslim women all
used the Ottoman courts--

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:36.350
the Sharia courts to
their advantage especially

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:38.990
for economic transactions.

00:19:38.990 --> 00:19:40.970
They bought and sold property.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:44.250
They inherited and
passed on their wealth,

00:19:44.250 --> 00:19:48.940
established endowments, borrowed
and lent money and [inaudible]

00:19:48.940 --> 00:19:51.230
or partners in businesses.

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:55.870
So, this literature has
really restored the agency

00:19:55.870 --> 00:20:04.140
of these women who had
previously appeared if at all

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:08.640
as with one scholar has called
passive orientalist caricatures

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:10.470
in the scholar literature.

00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:12.550
So, there has been
great enthusiasm

00:20:12.550 --> 00:20:16.810
in using these court records
to document women's agency.

00:20:16.810 --> 00:20:22.730
And some scholars have
taken this to argue that--

00:20:22.730 --> 00:20:27.420
to question the existence
of patriarchy

00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:28.720
in the Ottoman Empire.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:32.690
I wouldn't go as far as to
say that, but I would say

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:35.910
that it's important to
recognize that women had--

00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:39.090
Muslim women had certainly
privileges that distinguish them

00:20:39.090 --> 00:20:42.430
from their counterparts
in most early European--

00:20:42.430 --> 00:20:45.550
early modern European
societies who liked many

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:49.690
of the same rights,
especially in two areas,

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:54.320
in property and marriage.

00:20:54.320 --> 00:21:00.040
And this is because women had
full legal rights as individuals

00:21:00.040 --> 00:21:03.950
which in certain fields were
indistinguishable from males.

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:09.140
So for example in the types
of property they could inherit

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:11.920
or in the management
of their property.

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:15.300
Some of you probably
already know

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:18.640
that there's a standard half
share of inheritance business

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:22.070
in inheritance law, but
they regularly inherit it

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:25.320
from both their own families
and in their marriages.

00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:26.760
And their rights in managing

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:31.810
that property were
identical to male rights.

00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:34.670
So even though the law
and its application

00:21:34.670 --> 00:21:38.360
and its interpretation
clearly favored men over women,

00:21:38.360 --> 00:21:40.940
nevertheless women could seek
justice in the courts based

00:21:40.940 --> 00:21:44.780
on these legal rights
and seek justice.

00:21:44.780 --> 00:21:47.590
So just for comparison,
if we compare this

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:54.070
to the Married Women's Property
Act, the various acts in 1870

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:57.490
in the United Kingdom
and then in the mid 1800s

00:21:57.490 --> 00:22:02.980
in the United States, this is
just as a point of reference

00:22:02.980 --> 00:22:07.760
to highlight the fact that
legally, Muslim women,

00:22:07.760 --> 00:22:10.340
and in this case we're
talking about Ottoman women,

00:22:10.340 --> 00:22:15.550
had these rights that were their
inalienable rights for many,

00:22:15.550 --> 00:22:19.570
many centuries before
European women got them

00:22:19.570 --> 00:22:22.110
in the 19th century.

00:22:22.110 --> 00:22:25.200
So, this is from New York.

00:22:25.200 --> 00:22:28.520
New York's Married Women's
Property Act became a model

00:22:28.520 --> 00:22:32.010
for other states in that period.

00:22:32.010 --> 00:22:35.080
So, I really want to clarify
that my point here is not

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:38.870
to compare one kind of
patriarchy over the other

00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:40.680
or to think about
which one is better.

00:22:40.680 --> 00:22:47.000
But rather, it is to highlight
the fact that patriarchy existed

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.820
and I'm interested in
how women used the courts

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:53.450
to contest this patriarchal
gender religious hierarchy

00:22:53.450 --> 00:22:55.010
in the Ottoman Empire.

00:22:55.010 --> 00:22:56.920
So, one scholar,
Deniz Kandiyoti,

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:00.010
has used the term
patriarchal bargain for this.

00:23:00.010 --> 00:23:03.180
So, women were literally
bargaining with the patriarchy

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:11.360
to make it work for them, but
still working within the system.

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:12.660
All right.

00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:19.550
So then in my snapshots today,
I decided to give you examples

00:23:19.550 --> 00:23:22.670
from three broad areas.

00:23:22.670 --> 00:23:25.130
One, some things
that I talk about,

00:23:25.130 --> 00:23:28.880
the women's economic activism
or financial activities

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:35.120
in court briefly, then about
family law, mainly marriage--

00:23:35.120 --> 00:23:41.110
mainly divorce and remarriage,
and also matters of public order

00:23:41.110 --> 00:23:45.190
and the business
of expelling women

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:51.520
from certain neighborhoods, so
literally just small snapshots.

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:54.550
And I also want to
point out that

00:23:54.550 --> 00:24:00.770
as in other early modern cities
at the-- in the 18th century,

00:24:00.770 --> 00:24:03.340
poverty was rampant
in Ottoman Istanbul.

00:24:03.340 --> 00:24:06.760
So some of the women that
we encounter in the courts,

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:10.700
we can assume that
they are middle class

00:24:10.700 --> 00:24:13.960
or have some access
to the courts.

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:15.930
There was a very
highly developed culture

00:24:15.930 --> 00:24:17.230
of going to the court.

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:18.920
Women knew about the courts.

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:21.420
And there is this famous
saying that, you know,

00:24:21.420 --> 00:24:24.460
men couldn't stop women from
going to the court, going--

00:24:24.460 --> 00:24:25.810
and going to the hammam,

00:24:25.810 --> 00:24:27.300
basically to the
public bath, right?

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:29.650
So, it was a legitimate
thing to do to go to court.

00:24:29.650 --> 00:24:33.590
Our understanding is that
court fees were not exorbitant.

00:24:33.590 --> 00:24:35.190
They were affordable.

00:24:35.190 --> 00:24:37.220
We also know that very--

00:24:37.220 --> 00:24:40.280
upper middle class and elite
families didn't typically go

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:41.580
to courts.

00:24:41.580 --> 00:24:43.630
So, they try to resolve
matters among themselves,

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:45.800
not to being shame
to the family.

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:47.880
So, it was a last
resort for them.

00:24:47.880 --> 00:24:51.560
But the types of women who
regularly used the courts seem

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:56.430
to be sort of middle
class urban women

00:24:56.430 --> 00:25:00.020
with some exemptions of course.

00:25:00.020 --> 00:25:02.530
All right.

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:05.540
So when we look at women's
financial activities,

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:11.860
we see again from these
records the use of court records

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:15.150
that Ottoman women were quite
active in the urban economy

00:25:15.150 --> 00:25:23.010
of Istanbul as borrowers of
money, as lenders of money,

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:26.090
as property owners,
buyers and sellers,

00:25:26.090 --> 00:25:27.810
founders of endowments
[inaudible].

00:25:27.810 --> 00:25:32.280
They were managers of businesses
and they were landladies.

00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:37.260
Middle class women were
very active in setting

00:25:37.260 --> 00:25:41.980
up these small charitable
family foundations

00:25:41.980 --> 00:25:46.790
that typically statistically
most often included residential

00:25:46.790 --> 00:25:52.080
units, fountains, hammams,
public baths and rental shops.

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:54.910
They-- And they usually set up
their family members, husbands,

00:25:54.910 --> 00:25:58.090
but especially their children
and frequently their daughters

00:25:58.090 --> 00:26:00.670
and their slaves,
female slaves as their--

00:26:00.670 --> 00:26:06.750
as the beneficiaries of these
foundations, endowments,

00:26:06.750 --> 00:26:08.880
and managers of the endowments.

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:13.060
And so, their wealth typically
came from two sources.

00:26:13.060 --> 00:26:16.810
I-- As I mentioned a little
while ago, part of it came

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:20.880
from inheritance because
women had inheritance rights.

00:26:20.880 --> 00:26:23.710
So, they inherit it from
their own family members.

00:26:23.710 --> 00:26:26.720
And then another
source of wealth

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:30.330
for women was upon marriage,
the dowry that they receive,

00:26:30.330 --> 00:26:32.760
that's part of their
marriage contract.

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:39.980
So, a lot of women who had
sizeable wealth and by that,

00:26:39.980 --> 00:26:43.510
I don't mean necessarily
huge amounts of wealth,

00:26:43.510 --> 00:26:46.150
but large enough to
invest in something,

00:26:46.150 --> 00:26:48.140
took this money and
invested it in.

00:26:48.140 --> 00:26:52.690
So even though their wealth
came through passive means,

00:26:52.690 --> 00:26:56.520
if you will, so they weren't
going out and making money,

00:26:56.520 --> 00:26:58.860
they received it through
inheritance in marriage,

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:03.710
they were active in
investing this money.

00:27:03.710 --> 00:27:08.360
We also see that they--
in addition to the courts,

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:10.070
see these various
courts in Istanbul,

00:27:10.070 --> 00:27:12.570
they also used the
Imperial Council

00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:16.400
and they petitioned
directly to monarch for cases

00:27:16.400 --> 00:27:20.160
that weren't resolved within
the usual court procedures.

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:25.480
And so, they took
their grievances

00:27:25.480 --> 00:27:30.380
to the monarch directly in this
process of bargaining in order

00:27:30.380 --> 00:27:33.150
to manipulate the
existing legal system

00:27:33.150 --> 00:27:36.640
to make it work better for them.

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:40.200
But again, I want to sort
of qualify this by saying

00:27:40.200 --> 00:27:43.410
that I would not take
this as far as to suggest

00:27:43.410 --> 00:27:46.930
that this gave women complete
control of their lives.

00:27:46.930 --> 00:27:50.040
So, this activism in this
agency is very important,

00:27:50.040 --> 00:27:52.970
but we have to remember
the broader context.

00:27:52.970 --> 00:27:56.350
So, I wouldn't go as far as
saying that this activism

00:27:56.350 --> 00:28:00.720
in courts is a direct proof of
women's control of their lives.

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:02.310
It is a huge privilege compared

00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:06.970
to other women around--
at the same time.

00:28:12.650 --> 00:28:17.390
So, women who are aware of these
advantages made it their regular

00:28:17.390 --> 00:28:18.690
business to go to the courts.

00:28:18.690 --> 00:28:20.230
And the courts were different

00:28:20.230 --> 00:28:24.990
than how we imagine the courts
today and that the qadi courts,

00:28:24.990 --> 00:28:27.560
the Sharia courts of the
Ottoman Empire worked also

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:29.920
as a kind of public notary.

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:32.690
So any kind of business contract
you have, you would take it

00:28:32.690 --> 00:28:36.680
to the magistrate or the judge,
the qadi to officiate, right,

00:28:36.680 --> 00:28:40.880
like I could enter a contract
with the neighbor for a rental,

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:42.490
something or some
kind of arrangement.

00:28:42.490 --> 00:28:45.770
Without the qadi's seal, that
wouldn't be an official paper.

00:28:45.770 --> 00:28:47.730
So, there are all kinds of
things in these court records,

00:28:47.730 --> 00:28:51.820
not just criminal court
records for example.

00:28:51.820 --> 00:28:53.440
So, they can tell us about--

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:54.740
a lot about the types

00:28:54.740 --> 00:28:58.480
of activities urban
women were involved in.

00:28:58.480 --> 00:29:05.340
When we move on to family
law, especially marriage,

00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:08.350
issues of marriage,
divorce and remarriage,

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:13.760
let's look at what kinds
of rights the Sharia

00:29:13.760 --> 00:29:16.410
or Islamic principles-- and
the Ottomans follow the Hanafi

00:29:16.410 --> 00:29:21.460
School of Law, for those of
you who are knowledgeable

00:29:21.460 --> 00:29:26.600
of the different schools of
law in the Islamic context.

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:32.110
So, Hanafi Law and Ottoman
application of the law specified

00:29:32.110 --> 00:29:35.100
that upon marriage contract,
the woman should receive a dowry

00:29:35.100 --> 00:29:38.440
from her husband, which then
became an inalienable part

00:29:38.440 --> 00:29:42.700
of her private property, legally
and technically untouchable

00:29:42.700 --> 00:29:47.580
by any male relative including
her husband once she had reached

00:29:47.580 --> 00:29:48.880
legal majority.

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:52.040
So sometimes, marriages were
arranged before women reached

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:54.850
puberty, and they had
the right to contest

00:29:54.850 --> 00:29:59.930
that arranged marriage
once they reached puberty.

00:30:01.120 --> 00:30:03.500
And there are many cases
in the court records

00:30:03.500 --> 00:30:08.570
where we see women come to
court, their husbands have gone,

00:30:08.570 --> 00:30:10.530
they're either missing
or they've gone--

00:30:10.530 --> 00:30:12.850
they've joined a military
campaign or they've gone

00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:14.470
on a business trip of some sort

00:30:14.470 --> 00:30:18.540
but they've been
gone for a long time.

00:30:18.540 --> 00:30:23.480
And so we see women
go to court in order

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:26.570
to request the maintenance that
they're due from their husbands.

00:30:26.570 --> 00:30:28.380
There is actually
a daily maintenance

00:30:28.380 --> 00:30:33.330
that every woman is
legally entitled to.

00:30:33.330 --> 00:30:36.360
And if the husband fails to
pay that maintenance to her

00:30:36.360 --> 00:30:39.580
or provide that to her-- for
her, she can go to the judge

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:44.400
and say this is not
happening and I need it.

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:48.000
And in the cases when the
husband is either unable

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:52.000
to financially pay or
is away and missing

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.590
or for whatever reason
he's unable to pay,

00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:58.860
the courts grant the woman
the right to borrow that money

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:00.200
on behalf of her husband.

00:31:00.200 --> 00:31:03.760
So she borrows money and her
husband is legally required

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:05.060
to pay it back.

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:07.490
All right, so we see
women do that a lot.

00:31:07.490 --> 00:31:09.530
There are a lot of
records of those.

00:31:09.530 --> 00:31:17.800
But also upon divorce or
abandonment, women are entitled

00:31:17.800 --> 00:31:21.820
to what's referred to as a
delayed portion of the dower

00:31:21.820 --> 00:31:27.430
of the marital gift, if
you will, that's hers.

00:31:27.430 --> 00:31:29.500
And so we see women go to court

00:31:29.500 --> 00:31:33.780
with their marriage
contracts asking the judge

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:39.600
for the differed portion of
their dower upon divorce.

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:44.130
So before I move on
to some examples,

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:48.440
I want to make a few
additional points.

00:31:48.440 --> 00:31:53.270
So we see that in according
to Sharia principles,

00:31:53.270 --> 00:31:56.230
consent to marriage
is legally required.

00:31:56.230 --> 00:31:59.140
So the woman has the
right to contest it

00:31:59.140 --> 00:32:01.640
if for some reason she's been--

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:04.160
either her marriage has been
arranged before she was legal --

00:32:04.160 --> 00:32:07.030
of legal age, which is puberty.

00:32:07.030 --> 00:32:11.600
Or for some reason she has
changed her mind and they were--

00:32:11.600 --> 00:32:14.020
even though men had
easier access to divorce,

00:32:14.020 --> 00:32:17.000
women had legitimate
reasons to ask for a divorce.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:19.860
And we'll talk about a
few of those in a minute.

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:28.990
So how many of you have heard
of the unilateral divorce

00:32:28.990 --> 00:32:32.110
in the Islamic law, talaq?

00:32:32.110 --> 00:32:35.050
A few people.

00:32:35.050 --> 00:32:38.570
So, in classical
Islamic Law, men--

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:41.780
Muslim men have the right to
unilaterally divorce their wives

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:45.820
without going to court
or providing the reason,

00:32:45.820 --> 00:32:47.800
a legitimate reason for it.

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:49.960
Women don't have the same right.

00:32:49.960 --> 00:32:53.030
They have to proof-- they
bear the burden of proof.

00:32:53.030 --> 00:32:54.750
So they have to go
in court and prove

00:32:54.750 --> 00:32:58.410
that they have a legitimate
reason to ask for a divorce.

00:32:58.410 --> 00:33:00.710
So while a man can
say I divorce you,

00:33:00.710 --> 00:33:02.670
and there's a famous
triple formula,

00:33:02.670 --> 00:33:05.820
so if he says it three
times, that's a divorce

00:33:05.820 --> 00:33:08.730
and he is not required to go
register it in the courts.

00:33:08.730 --> 00:33:11.910
The only reason we know is
because women go to court

00:33:11.910 --> 00:33:16.720
and say he divorced me and
I need him to pay me either

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:19.810
because of custody
issues or because

00:33:19.810 --> 00:33:23.520
of supporting her
and the children.

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:25.870
So we only know through
women who go

00:33:25.870 --> 00:33:27.700
to court to contest it, right.

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:30.790
So I'm interested-- I'm
more interested today

00:33:30.790 --> 00:33:35.090
in telling you about,
you know, what happens

00:33:35.090 --> 00:33:38.460
or under what circumstances
women could ask for a divorce

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:41.110
and how the courts handle that,

00:33:41.110 --> 00:33:46.300
and again how women used the
courts to make the system work

00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:47.890
to the best of their advantage,

00:33:47.890 --> 00:33:50.780
under difficult circumstances,
obviously.

00:33:50.780 --> 00:33:54.920
So, a Muslim woman's
opportunities

00:33:54.920 --> 00:33:56.690
for seeking divorce
included first

00:33:56.690 --> 00:33:59.980
and foremost the stipulations
in their marriage contract.

00:33:59.980 --> 00:34:07.940
So any marriage that has been
recorded in the courts have

00:34:07.940 --> 00:34:10.770
to include a marriage contract.

00:34:10.770 --> 00:34:14.720
And oftentimes, women could
restrict the conditions

00:34:14.720 --> 00:34:17.410
in their contract under which
the husband could pronounce the

00:34:17.410 --> 00:34:18.710
unilateral divorce.

00:34:18.710 --> 00:34:20.740
So there are some
marriage contracts

00:34:20.740 --> 00:34:24.370
where the husband gives up
that right, for example,

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:28.070
and it's written
in the contract.

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:31.530
Or oftentimes there were
stipulations that said

00:34:31.530 --> 00:34:35.820
if he is missing or if he
is gone for so many number

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:41.230
of years, then that's a
legitimate reason for a divorce.

00:34:41.230 --> 00:34:45.530
So disappearance,
abandonment, lack of support.

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:49.430
So if a husband is not
sufficiently supporting his

00:34:49.430 --> 00:34:51.620
family, his wife-- this
is really about the wife,

00:34:51.620 --> 00:34:54.030
not the family as a whole,
children are not part

00:34:54.030 --> 00:34:57.830
of this picture that I am
talking about currently.

00:34:57.830 --> 00:35:02.090
Mental instability, so
madness is a specific category

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:05.620
and there is a broad
category of harm, right.

00:35:05.620 --> 00:35:08.880
So if a woman could
prove in court

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:12.220
that her husband is mentally
or physically abusing her

00:35:12.220 --> 00:35:15.710
or causing her harm, that's a
legitimate reason for a divorce.

00:35:15.710 --> 00:35:18.430
Of course how would
you prove that?

00:35:18.430 --> 00:35:22.630
That's the tricky part but
these are legal categories.

00:35:22.630 --> 00:35:24.500
Blasphemy is another
valid ground

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:26.630
for annulling the marriage.

00:35:26.630 --> 00:35:30.230
But a very common scenario in
the court records is a story

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:33.120
of missing husbands
and deserted wives.

00:35:33.120 --> 00:35:35.400
Like, so what happens
to these women

00:35:35.400 --> 00:35:39.980
when the husbands desert
them for various reasons?

00:35:39.980 --> 00:35:45.650
So the courts were prepared
to deal with this issue.

00:35:45.650 --> 00:35:48.640
Because when men disappeared,
most women were left

00:35:48.640 --> 00:35:50.210
without any resources, right.

00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:51.510
They might have a small--

00:35:51.510 --> 00:35:56.480
the lucky ones might have
a small amount of money.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:35:59.130
They might have invested in
something or collecting rent

00:35:59.130 --> 00:36:01.790
of some sort or maybe
working in some capacity

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:07.820
but most women relied on
family resources for survival.

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:17.730
Among divorce cases, the most
common form of termination,

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:20.870
or a divorce that was
initiated by women,

00:36:20.870 --> 00:36:23.470
is what's called
a woman's divorce

00:36:23.470 --> 00:36:25.600
or a female-initiated divorce

00:36:25.600 --> 00:36:28.980
that involved the
woman's voluntary--

00:36:28.980 --> 00:36:35.250
the woman giving up her right to
the delayed portion of the dower

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:38.240
that is by law owed
to her, right.

00:36:38.240 --> 00:36:43.600
So if she can't prove any other
legitimate reason for a divorce

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:46.770
and the husband is not
consenting, then she can give

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:49.760
up that chunk of
money that's owed her

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:52.270
for support after divorce.

00:36:52.270 --> 00:36:56.260
So, in a way, she is buying
her husband's marital rights

00:36:56.260 --> 00:36:59.410
from him in return
for the divorce.

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:03.830
So, again, scholars have
written quite a lot about this.

00:37:03.830 --> 00:37:07.100
My colleague Matt
[inaudible] who's at University

00:37:07.100 --> 00:37:09.680
of Maryland College Park here
has written about this type

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:14.380
of divorce and it's questionable
to what extent this type

00:37:14.380 --> 00:37:16.950
of divorce was empowering
to women.

00:37:16.950 --> 00:37:18.250
Because on the one hand,

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:21.410
it shows that the woman
could divorce her husband.

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:25.050
And once he gives up that right,
it's almost automatic divorce.

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:28.220
He doesn't have to deal with
anything, any of the messy parts

00:37:28.220 --> 00:37:29.890
of the divorce after that.

00:37:29.890 --> 00:37:32.720
But how many women could do
that, we can assume that women

00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:36.440
who had the financial resources
to support themselves could do

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:40.480
that or had the networks, family
networks, or community networks.

00:37:40.480 --> 00:37:44.910
But we can assume that
a lot of women stayed

00:37:44.910 --> 00:37:47.960
in miserable marriages
because they couldn't do that.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:53.450
So it's-- the consequences
are complex.

00:37:53.450 --> 00:37:54.750
And when women did that,

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:56.780
they also automatically
lost the custody

00:37:56.780 --> 00:37:58.380
of their children, right.

00:37:58.380 --> 00:37:59.680
So there was a lot at stake.

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:01.200
On the one hand,
you have this right.

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:04.130
But on the other hand,
it was complicated.

00:38:04.130 --> 00:38:07.670
So now let's look at
a couple of examples.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:09.850
We passed this.

00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:14.960
Oh, we're going the other way.

00:38:14.960 --> 00:38:21.390
Here. So, in this court case
