00:47:16.430 --> 00:47:19.900
but for complicated reasons.

00:47:19.900 --> 00:47:22.270
So for non-Muslim
women converting

00:47:22.270 --> 00:47:25.950
to Islam offered an escape from
what may be more unbearable

00:47:25.950 --> 00:47:29.400
or more patriarchal depending
on the context situations

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:32.230
in their own communities.

00:47:32.230 --> 00:47:36.940
And conversion also gave them
the custody of their children.

00:47:36.940 --> 00:47:40.700
So if a non-Muslim woman
went to court and converted,

00:47:40.700 --> 00:47:44.410
not only was she immediately
divorced from her husband

00:47:44.410 --> 00:47:47.270
but she also immediately gained
the custody of her children

00:47:47.270 --> 00:47:52.970
to raise them as Muslim children
which was otherwise complicated.

00:47:57.920 --> 00:48:02.570
So there were certain privileges
to conversion obviously.

00:48:02.570 --> 00:48:04.860
But again, what I
want to highlight,

00:48:04.860 --> 00:48:08.200
I agree with my colleague
Marc Baer, that this was a way

00:48:08.200 --> 00:48:12.670
for women to opt out of one
type of patriarchal system

00:48:12.670 --> 00:48:16.430
into another one that in some
ways gave them more options

00:48:16.430 --> 00:48:20.460
but nevertheless also sustained
and recreated this patriarchy

00:48:20.460 --> 00:48:21.760
over and over again, right.

00:48:21.760 --> 00:48:25.590
Because they're opting into a
system that in some ways better

00:48:25.590 --> 00:48:30.670
in this context but did
not challenge the working

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:33.360
of the patriarchal system.

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:42.300
And then there were also
slave women who converted.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:49.850
And I would say that in
a-- in an Islamic empire,

00:48:49.850 --> 00:48:54.970
a multiethnic, multireligious
Islamic empire, slave--

00:48:54.970 --> 00:48:57.780
non-Muslim slaves were
at the very bottom

00:48:57.780 --> 00:48:59.100
of the hierarchy, right.

00:48:59.100 --> 00:49:02.050
So a non-Muslim slave
woman had the most to gain

00:49:02.050 --> 00:49:05.540
from conversion, right,
because of certain things.

00:49:05.540 --> 00:49:11.870
So, one, when a non-Muslim
slave converted,

00:49:11.870 --> 00:49:14.390
she could not any
longer be or he--

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:16.790
I'm talking mainly about
women, so I can say she--

00:49:16.790 --> 00:49:19.010
she could not any
longer be owned

00:49:19.010 --> 00:49:22.870
by a non-Muslim slave
owner, right.

00:49:22.870 --> 00:49:29.090
So if I convert as a slave
to Islam and I have a Jewish

00:49:29.090 --> 00:49:32.400
or a Christian owner, then
the authorities have the right

00:49:32.400 --> 00:49:36.780
to come and take me from
his position to make sure

00:49:36.780 --> 00:49:40.010
that I'm going to be
owned by a Muslim family.

00:49:40.010 --> 00:49:43.330
So that would be-- And that
tended to be the kind of thing

00:49:43.330 --> 00:49:46.080
that Muslim elites
like to do, right.

00:49:46.080 --> 00:49:50.210
So to sort of bring into
your household a newly--

00:49:50.210 --> 00:49:55.360
a new convert into a Muslim
household was almost understood

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:58.500
as a good act of
good faith, right.

00:49:58.500 --> 00:50:03.390
So that gave women an
opportunity to go from maybe

00:50:03.390 --> 00:50:08.320
of a commoner to an elite
Muslim household, right.

00:50:08.320 --> 00:50:11.170
But of course also, the best
thing that could happen was

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:15.070
for a woman, a slave woman
who converted to Islam

00:50:15.070 --> 00:50:20.430
to marry her master and
bear children for him.

00:50:20.430 --> 00:50:26.230
When a slave woman had
children with free Muslim men,

00:50:26.230 --> 00:50:29.850
her children were
born slate free.

00:50:29.850 --> 00:50:31.840
They were now born into slavery.

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:34.830
And in many cases, the
owners could free the

00:50:34.830 --> 00:50:36.130
woman immediately.

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:39.090
But if they did not do
that, when the owner died,

00:50:39.090 --> 00:50:41.970
the slave automatically
became free, right,

00:50:41.970 --> 00:50:45.490
without any contestation.

00:50:45.490 --> 00:50:48.630
So-- And not only that, but
she became an equal heir

00:50:48.630 --> 00:50:49.930
to his estate.

00:50:49.930 --> 00:50:54.960
So not only did her children
inherit equal shares as children

00:50:54.960 --> 00:50:57.170
from other marriages,
but she also inherited

00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:00.070
as an equal wife
in that marriage.

00:51:00.070 --> 00:51:03.640
So we see a lot of such
records in the courts,

00:51:03.640 --> 00:51:10.320
former slaves going to court
to do paperwork for inheritance

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:14.490
and division of certain shares
of estates and so forth.

00:51:14.490 --> 00:51:19.570
Yeah, so here is one account
that I wanted to put up here.

00:51:19.570 --> 00:51:23.370
I'm going to go quickly
through this now.

00:51:23.370 --> 00:51:28.060
Here's an account of
a record in the courts

00:51:28.060 --> 00:51:30.860
for a woman being freed
after having children.

00:51:30.860 --> 00:51:39.860
The last type of thing I want to
bring up is the issue of women--

00:51:39.860 --> 00:51:43.190
another way that women
we're very vulnerable living

00:51:43.190 --> 00:51:46.050
in neighborhoods, especially
women who lived on their own.

00:51:46.050 --> 00:51:49.440
So this could be women who
were widowed or divorced

00:51:49.440 --> 00:51:53.570
or for some other reason lived
alone which would be rare.

00:51:53.570 --> 00:51:58.650
But Ottoman government
and society in the absence

00:51:58.650 --> 00:52:01.130
of modern police institutions

00:52:01.130 --> 00:52:08.640
until the 19th century
used community policing

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:12.480
like community watches to police
themselves as small communities.

00:52:12.480 --> 00:52:16.140
So it was everybody
else's business to spy

00:52:16.140 --> 00:52:18.400
on everybody else basically.

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:20.570
It was very functional in some
ways which, you can imagine,

00:52:20.570 --> 00:52:23.520
it put women and people
who were marginalized

00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:25.380
in a vulnerable position.

00:52:25.380 --> 00:52:28.510
So my own research for
my own book research,

00:52:28.510 --> 00:52:30.080
I work with some
of these records.

00:52:30.080 --> 00:52:34.010
I was interested in
matters of public order

00:52:34.010 --> 00:52:35.780
and disorder in neighborhoods.

00:52:35.780 --> 00:52:38.200
And my research in
the court records show

00:52:38.200 --> 00:52:42.150
that this was the most
common type of complaint

00:52:42.150 --> 00:52:45.330
about public order in
neighborhoods, that is,

00:52:45.330 --> 00:52:47.480
a group of residents

00:52:47.480 --> 00:52:50.030
in the neighborhood get
together, they go to the qadi.

00:52:50.030 --> 00:52:52.470
They're usually the imam
and religious leaders

00:52:52.470 --> 00:52:55.360
of the neighborhood are
with them and they complain

00:52:55.360 --> 00:52:59.580
about a group of women
or entire families.

00:52:59.580 --> 00:53:04.480
And basically the language used
in the records is very sort

00:53:04.480 --> 00:53:07.640
of standardized probably
not the language

00:53:07.640 --> 00:53:11.770
that the petitioners
use themselves.

00:53:11.770 --> 00:53:17.750
But they found-- they
claimed that people were unfit

00:53:17.750 --> 00:53:21.260
to live among them because
of various criminal behavior

00:53:21.260 --> 00:53:22.810
or bad morals.

00:53:22.810 --> 00:53:24.300
They didn't mind
their own business.

00:53:24.300 --> 00:53:26.570
They didn't live
a righteous life.

00:53:26.570 --> 00:53:31.230
For women, the accusations
were usually

00:53:31.230 --> 00:53:35.580
about being disruptive
or dishonest.

00:53:35.580 --> 00:53:39.300
This is probably a cover
up for not being virtuous.

00:53:39.300 --> 00:53:43.790
For improper dress,
being verbally abusive,

00:53:43.790 --> 00:53:48.880
using offensive language,
receiving unidentified men

00:53:48.880 --> 00:53:53.290
and women in their residences,
disregarding multiple warning,

00:53:53.290 --> 00:53:56.560
so there was a warning system
but disregarding these warnings,

00:53:56.560 --> 00:54:03.380
and making such deeds-- misdeeds
a habit, so habitual behavior.

00:54:03.380 --> 00:54:06.980
And in all of these cases,
and here is one example,

00:54:06.980 --> 00:54:09.480
the accused allegedly
disrupted peace and order

00:54:09.480 --> 00:54:10.780
in the neighborhood

00:54:10.780 --> 00:54:17.940
so the residents did not want
them in that neighborhood.

00:54:17.940 --> 00:54:20.440
And I have to stress
here that many times

00:54:20.440 --> 00:54:24.440
in these records women
also appear as petitioners.

00:54:24.440 --> 00:54:28.350
So women we can say were also
the watchdogs of their sisters.

00:54:28.350 --> 00:54:31.540
So it wasn't just men spying
on women or men trying

00:54:31.540 --> 00:54:32.840
to get women expelled.

00:54:32.840 --> 00:54:35.340
There were often a lot of
women in the groups as well.

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:36.640
And these groups were mixed.

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:38.360
A lot of Ottoman
neighborhoods were mixed.

00:54:38.360 --> 00:54:42.260
So Muslim and non-Muslim races
would come together to ask

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:45.810
for the expulsion
of certain people.

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:50.780
I think I had a number
of examples

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:53.550
but this is again a scene.

00:54:53.550 --> 00:54:58.060
It's entitled from the same
work as the "Brothel at Night"

00:54:58.060 --> 00:55:02.660
but they could just as well be
curious neighbors questioning

00:55:02.660 --> 00:55:05.180
the integrity of these women
who really, if they were

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:06.740
on their own, didn't
really have a lot

00:55:06.740 --> 00:55:11.170
of ways socially acceptable
ways to defend themselves.

00:55:11.170 --> 00:55:15.130
So in this picture, you can
see there are some Janissaries

00:55:15.130 --> 00:55:17.220
who worked, were
usually like the police.

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:19.940
So the imam probably
receives a complaint

00:55:19.940 --> 00:55:23.260
and he goes knocking
on the door.

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:26.240
But even in these
cases where allegedly

00:55:26.240 --> 00:55:30.060
in this case Fatma
Hatun was caught

00:55:30.060 --> 00:55:31.870
with them indecently, right.

00:55:31.870 --> 00:55:35.130
This is really sort of
covered up language, right.

00:55:35.130 --> 00:55:39.290
That could be a cover up for
an accusation for prostitution.

00:55:39.290 --> 00:55:41.250
And it was really stunning
to see in the records

00:55:41.250 --> 00:55:42.550
that the accusations

00:55:42.550 --> 00:55:46.100
for prostitution directly
are almost nonexistent.

00:55:46.100 --> 00:55:47.950
Instead, you see
these bad morals

00:55:47.950 --> 00:55:49.250
and we don't want them here.

00:55:49.250 --> 00:55:52.810
So the question of what
happens to these women comes up.

00:55:52.810 --> 00:55:55.330
There is no way of tracing
them unless they come back

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:57.970
to court to ask for something.

00:55:57.970 --> 00:56:03.170
So there are cases where--
I believe I have one here.

00:56:03.170 --> 00:56:05.920
Yeah, so in this case--

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:16.990
In this one, they say
they leave immediately.

00:56:16.990 --> 00:56:25.330
In this one, three
years has-- had past.

00:56:25.330 --> 00:56:31.430
So a group of residents went
to court and got a warrant,

00:56:31.430 --> 00:56:34.010
if you will, an order for
these women to be expelled

00:56:34.010 --> 00:56:35.310
from the neighborhood.

00:56:35.310 --> 00:56:37.200
And then three years
later, they go back

00:56:37.200 --> 00:56:39.390
to court saying they're
still here.

00:56:39.390 --> 00:56:42.170
We came to court three years
ago, you said they would go.

00:56:42.170 --> 00:56:47.490
So there's-- my point here is
that until modern nation states,

00:56:47.490 --> 00:56:49.850
the state itself had
very little power

00:56:49.850 --> 00:56:52.680
over the implementation
of communal matters.

00:56:52.680 --> 00:56:56.380
So in a way, as annoying
as a spy might have been,

00:56:56.380 --> 00:57:00.910
local communities had a
lot of autonomy compared

00:57:00.910 --> 00:57:04.920
to how our governments sort of
know everything about us today

00:57:04.920 --> 00:57:06.380
and police us and control us.

00:57:06.380 --> 00:57:07.930
Well, in terms of
implementation,

00:57:07.930 --> 00:57:11.920
it was up to the community to
make sure that those people--

00:57:11.920 --> 00:57:15.630
my time is up-- that
those people left, right.

00:57:15.630 --> 00:57:19.160
So in most cases, we don't
know where people went,

00:57:19.160 --> 00:57:20.460
where these women went.

00:57:20.460 --> 00:57:22.730
There is some research that
shows that they just move--

00:57:22.730 --> 00:57:26.200
went to the neighborhood,
one neighborhood down.

00:57:26.200 --> 00:57:28.450
They didn't go very
far, they weren't exiled

00:57:28.450 --> 00:57:31.560
or they weren't punished
for their behavior.

00:57:31.560 --> 00:57:35.560
In fact, there's
research on prostitution

00:57:35.560 --> 00:57:38.770
in the Ottoman Empire
both from the Arab lands

00:57:38.770 --> 00:57:41.620
and in Turkish parts
of the Empire show

00:57:41.620 --> 00:57:45.210
that increasingly they were
being banished in this way.

00:57:45.210 --> 00:57:49.570
But the state wasn't even
outlawing prostitution based

00:57:49.570 --> 00:57:52.740
on immorality, they just
wanted to get this people

00:57:52.740 --> 00:57:54.870
out of the public's
sight, if you will, right.

00:57:54.870 --> 00:57:57.690
So there's this Arabic term
they use, tathir, right,

00:57:57.690 --> 00:58:02.370
to sort of cleanse the filth,
but make it invisible rather

00:58:02.370 --> 00:58:04.970
than stopping the deed itself.

00:58:04.970 --> 00:58:06.950
So women just went to
different neighborhoods.

00:58:06.950 --> 00:58:08.980
They were traveling from
one place to another.

00:58:08.980 --> 00:58:10.660
And we really don't know enough

00:58:10.660 --> 00:58:15.880
to know the real
implications of that for women.

00:58:15.880 --> 00:58:19.950
So I want to leave
on-- So, you know,

00:58:19.950 --> 00:58:22.390
a good note for women's agency.

00:58:22.390 --> 00:58:25.930
There were also a lot of women
like Serife Hatun in this case,

00:58:25.930 --> 00:58:28.220
who challenged the courts.

00:58:28.220 --> 00:58:32.030
You know, this-- she-- there was
a similar accusation about her

00:58:32.030 --> 00:58:36.760
and people thought she had
strangers in her dwellings.

00:58:36.760 --> 00:58:38.790
And then they came and
that was not the case.

00:58:38.790 --> 00:58:41.660
So she went to court and said
these people have shamed me

00:58:41.660 --> 00:58:45.590
publicly, so I want compensation
for that and she got it, right.

00:58:45.590 --> 00:58:48.690
So she challenged it and got
monetary compensation for it.

00:58:48.690 --> 00:58:53.550
And I want to end
with some images

00:58:53.550 --> 00:58:57.300
of Ottoman women
later 20th century.

00:58:57.300 --> 00:59:00.870
But as the Ottoman Empire
was transitioning, again,

00:59:00.870 --> 00:59:03.740
my point really has been
that this was a shared world

00:59:03.740 --> 00:59:07.590
for Muslim and non-Muslim
women under the Ottoman Empire.

00:59:07.590 --> 00:59:10.940
The same women started founding,
starting women's organizations

00:59:10.940 --> 00:59:13.130
in the 19th and 20th centuries.

00:59:13.130 --> 00:59:17.440
So this group, that included
Muslim and non-Muslim women,

00:59:17.440 --> 00:59:18.890
founded this association.

00:59:18.890 --> 00:59:23.040
And you see there's a plane,
a propeller in the background.

00:59:23.040 --> 00:59:25.530
They raised the money for
this plane and they bought it

00:59:25.530 --> 00:59:27.130
and they flew it themselves.

00:59:27.130 --> 00:59:30.130
They've been asking for
the permission to do it,

00:59:30.130 --> 00:59:32.450
nobody wanted to give them
permission or train then.

00:59:32.450 --> 00:59:34.920
So they raised the
money and did it anyway.

00:59:34.920 --> 00:59:38.630
And they distributed
fliers over Istanbul

00:59:38.630 --> 00:59:43.440
to publicize their
organization for women's rights.

00:59:43.440 --> 00:59:45.480
They founded this one
of the famous journals,

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:48.270
women's journals, again
Muslim and non-Muslim women.

00:59:48.270 --> 00:59:57.160
And I'm going to leave you with
this my Turkish suffragists,

00:59:57.160 --> 01:00:02.040
right, who campaigned for
universal suffrage in Turkey.

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:06.080
And they got in 1930 the
rights for local elections

01:00:06.080 --> 01:00:09.500
and then 1934 is when Turkish
women got universal suffrage.

01:00:09.500 --> 01:00:13.600
That's fairly early
compared to the global trend.

01:00:13.600 --> 01:00:18.330
So these Ottoman women
together achieved a lot things

01:00:18.330 --> 01:00:20.940
and I would argue that
it's a mistake to see them

01:00:20.940 --> 01:00:23.510
as separate entities and
communities in a binary way

01:00:23.510 --> 01:00:26.480
that we tend to do today
when it comes to Muslims.

